  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN182.1-kilavi"><app><lem>iravu varuvāṉaip</lem><rdg wit="#C5">tōḻi kūṟṟu</rdg><rdg wit="#C2 #C3 #RK">tōḻi</rdg><rdg wit="#C7">irāvantāṉaip</rdg><rdg wit="#C2 #C3">iravu vāṉaip<gap reason="lost" unit="character" quantity="8"/></rdg></app> pakal varaveṉṟatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">How it was said to the one who comes by night to come by day.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN182.1">
        <l>āṅkaṇ vēṅkai yoḷḷiṇar malaintu</l>
        <l>vāṅkamai nōṉcilai yeruttat tirīit</l>
        <l>tīmpaḻap palaviṉ cuḷai<supplied>viḷai</supplied> tēṟal</l>
        <l>vīḷai yampi ṉiḷaiyaroṭu mānti</l>
        <l>yōṭṭiyal piḻaiyā vayanāy piṟpaṭa</l>
        <l>vēṭṭam pōkiya kuṟavaṉ kāṭṭa</l>
        <l>kuḷavik kaṇpukal kurutiyoṭu tuyalvara</l>
        <l>muḷavumā tolaiccuṅ kuṉṟa nāṭa</l>
        <l>varaveṟi yurumō ṭaṉṟik kālvīḻt</l>
        <l>tiravumaḻai poḻinta pāṉāṭ kaṅkuṟ</l>
        <l>ṟaṉiyai vanta vāṟuniṉain talkalum</l>
        <l>paṉiyēr kaluḻumivaḷ kaṇṇē yataṉāṟ</l>
        <l>kaṭumpakal varutal vēṇṭun teyya</l>
        <l>vatirkuraṉ mutukalai kaṟimuṟi muṇaii</l>
        <l>yuyarcimai neṭuṅkōṭ ṭukaḷa vukka</l>
        <l>kamaḻita ḻalari tāay vēlaṉ</l>
        <l>veṟiyayar viyaṉkaḷaṅ kaṭukkum</l>
        <l>peruvarai naṇṇiya cāra lāṉē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>O man from a land of hills, (8cd)</l>
        <l>where the hill man who went for hunt, (6a-c)</l>
        <l>wearing bright clusters of kino from that place, (1)</l>
        <l>putting the sturdy bow of flexible bamboo on [his] neck, (2)</l>
        <l>[and] feeding, along with the youths with whistling arrows, (4)</l>
        <l>on toddy ripened from the pulp of sweet jack fruits, (3)</l>
        <l rend="indent8">destroys the porcupine, (6ab)</l>
        <l>while the strong dogs unfailing in [their] nature of chasing follow [him], (5)</l>
        <l>so that the wild jasmine comes into swinging with blood[-red petals], joyful for the eyes, (6df.)</l>
        <l>at midnight when nightly rain has poured, (10)</l>
        <l>driven by the wind, besides the thunder that afflicts snakes, (9)</l>
        <l>she thinks of the way you come alone (11a-c)</l>
        <l>[and] her eyes dim as tears well up all night. Therefore, (12df.)</l>
        <l>please, you must come by fierce midday, (13)</l>
        <l>– along the slope situated on the big mountain, (18)</l>
        <l>that resembles the wide floor prepared for the Veṟi dance (17)</l>
        <l>by the spear-bearing [priest], as flowers with fragrant petals are spread (16)</l>
        <l>that have dropped when the long branch on the high summit was jumped upon, (15)</l>
        <l>in dislike of pepper shoots, by the old male monkey with quaking voice. (14)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
